<font color="#FF0000">VIETNAM WAR</font><br>
<tt>Mon Nov 10  4:13:54 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
I am a 20 year old female; my father did not serve during the VW even though he was of age.  He went to college, and when he graduated he felt it was his duty to serve his country.  He enlisted; and was sure to go when the war stopped.  He had been thrown a going away party even when the war had just ended.  He did not go after all.  I guess the only thing that saved my father was timing.<br>
I am writing because of a memory from childhood that I'll never forget.  One day I asked my mother about the Vietnam war.  She told me about all the boys from her neighborhood that were sent-many of her friends had died in that war.  She started crying, just remembering that time of all the young men she knew who died.  I was very little, but I remember thinking how painful this must've been for her because 20 yrs. later the pain was fresh enough for her to cry about it, right in front of me.<br>
I guess I just wanted to share my thought about this one incident that has always stayed with me and how it affected my impressions and thoughts about the Vietnam war ever since
